Fill and boil your #kettle{}.

Pour the boiled water into a large #saucepan{} on medium heat.

Once boiling, add the @Egg Noodle Nest{2} to the water and cook until tender, ~{4%minutes}.

Once cooked, drain in a #sieve{} and run under cold water to stop them sticking together.

Meanwhile, halve the @Green Pepper{1} and discard the core and seeds. Slice into thin strips.

Heat a drizzle of @oil{drizzle} in large #frying pan{} on high heat.

Once hot, add the @British Beef Mince{240%g} and sliced pepper, then sprinkle over the @Thai Style Spice Mix{1} (add less if you'd prefer things milder).

Fry until the mince is browned and the pepper has softened, ~{5-6%minutes}. Use a #spoon{} to break up the mince as it cooks.

> IMPORTANT: Wash your hands and equipment after handling raw mince.

Meanwhile, cut the @Lime{1/2} into wedges.

Once the mince has browned, drain and discard any excess fat.

> IMPORTANT: The mince is cooked when no longer pink in the middle.

In a #small bowl{}, combine the @Ketjap Manis{50%ml}, @Honey{15%ml}, @Soy Sauce{25%ml} and @Tomato Ketchup{2%tbsp}. Add a good squeeze of lime juice and mix well.

> TIP: If your honey has hardened, pop it in a bowl of hot water for 1 min.

Add the sauce to the pan.

Bring to a simmer and bubble until thickened, ~{1-2%minutes}.

Add the cooked noodles to the spicy beef.

Stir to coat the noodles in the sauce and cook until everything's piping hot, ~{1-2%minutes}.

Add a splash of @?water{splash} if you feel it needs it.

Share the Thai inspired beef noodles between your bowls.

Serve with any remaining lime wedges for squeezing over. Enjoy!